{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17514155","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17514155"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:19:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:19:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12283"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12283","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12283"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.37,0.27,0.15,0.14,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4805"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114823"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4805","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4805"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12283"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96827"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"141"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7713"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7804"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13770"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33441"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42730"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43314"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45174"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45190"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48429"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114823","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114823"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 79-year-old woman is admitted under the orthogeriatric team following a fracture of the right neck of femur three days ago. She was about to shower when she slipped on her bathroom mat and fell on her right hip. She underwent a total hip arthroplasty two days ago and is currently recovering well from her surgery. Her history includes diabetes mellitus type 2 which is managed by metformin. Her last HbA1C level was 8.1%. Calcium and vitamin D level were performed yesterday all of which came back normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Start denosumab","DXA scan to confirm osteoporosis prior to initiating treatment","Recommend exercise therapy including strength training and hydrotherapy","Add dapagliflozin for better glucose control","Estimate absolute fracture risk using a recognised fracture risk calculator"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA diagnosis of osteoporosis can be made through clinical history of minimal trauma fracture at sites including the hip, distal radius, and/or thoracolumbar spine. A fractured neck of femur warrants treatment to prevent further fracture and bone loss, especially considering the associated morbidity and mortality. Treatment options include \u003Cstrong\u003Edenosumab\u003C/strong\u003E, which is an anti-resorptive medication. Anti-resorptive medications are currently considered first-line in the management of established osteoporosis, and these are usually given post-surgery once the patient has been stabilised. If the medication was not given during hospital admission, it is important for the team to follow up with the patient\u0027s general practitioner to ensure that the patient has received the medication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDenosumab or biphosphonates can be given as first-line treatment for osteoporosis. Prior to commencing these therapies, patient\u0027s should be vitamin D replete (\u0026gt;50 nmol/L) and normocalcaemic, due to the risk of hypocalcaemia. Patients should also be informed of adverse outcomes of denosumab and bisphosphonates, including osteonecrosis of the jaw and atypical femoral fracture, the latter of which occurs with increased duration of use. Denosumab is an acceptable option in elderly patients with \u0026lt;10 years life expectancy as its use beyond this duration is questioned/uncertain. It is readily available in the community, only requiring 6-monthly administration subcutaneously, making it preferable for some patients compared with weekly/monthly dosing of oral bisphosphonates, or intravenous bisphosphonates which can usually only be administered in the hospital setting and are associated with acute phase reactions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDXA scan\u003C/strong\u003E is recommended to be done to establish bone density baseline; however, it would not change clinical management as the patient has established osteoporosis. Treatment initiation should not be delayed to await a DXA result and initiation of treatment prior to a baseline DXA is unlikely to change the result.  It is important to note the contralateral femur would be examined with the DXA scan, as the fractured neck of femur would not be interpretable following total hip arthroplasty.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEstimate absolute fracture risk using a recognised fracture risk calculator \u003C/strong\u003Eis mostly indicated in patients with no history of minimal trauma hip/vertebral fracture, to help inform a patient\u0027s overall risk and help guide decision to treat. Two recognised calculators used in the Australian setting include FRAX and Garvan.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdd dapagliflozin for better glucose control\u003C/strong\u003E might theoretically improve the patient\u0027s glycaemic control; however, a HbA1c ~8% would not be an unreasonable target for glycaemic control given the patient\u0027s comorbidities. Further, it will not significantly address the patient\u0027s main problem which is currently her new diagnosis of osteoporosis. SGLT2 inhibitors may also slightly lower blood pressure through their modest diuretic effect, which could be problematic in a patient with a history of falls.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExercise therapy \u003C/strong\u003Ealone is not appropriate in this case. Due to her history of minimal trauma hip fracture, pharmacological management of osteoporosis should be commenced alongside with lifestyle changes. Lifestyle changes include exercise prescription, dietary changes, and smoking and alcohol cessation when appropriate. Strategies to prevent falls should also be thoroughly considered, including balance training, review of medications for polypharmacy, correction of visual/hearing impairment, proper fitting shoes, etc.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Anti-osteoporosis medication is indicated in minimal trauma hip/vertebral fracture"],"references":["Ebeling P, Center J, Clifton-Bligh R, Cooper M, et al. Osteoporosis prevention, diagnosis and management in postmenopausal women and men over 50 years of age - 2nd Edition. RACGP Clinical Guidelines. 2017. Viewed November 2022","RACGP. \u201cOsteoporosis Management and Fracture Prevention in Post-Menopausal Women and Men \u003E 50 Years of Age \u2013 Summary of Recommendations.\u201d RACGP, 2024, www.racgp.org.au/clinical-resources/clinical-guidelines/key-racgp-guidelines/view-all-racgp-guidelines/osteoporosis/summary-of-recommendations. Accessed 14 Apr. 2025.","Stuckey B, Magraith K, Opie N, Zhu K. Fracture risk prediction and the decision to treat low bone density. Australian journal of general practice. 2021 Mar;50(3):165-70."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96827"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12283"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96827","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96827"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-20T17:14:12+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-20T17:15:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4805"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114823"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self"